TYPE CONVERSIONS ,PROMOTIONS AND CASTING 

1. Which of these is necessary condition for automatic type conversion in Java?
a) The destination type is smaller than source type
b) The destination type is larger than source type
c) The destination type can be larger or smaller than source type
d) None of the mentioned
Answer: b
Explanation: Assignment of a smaller data type to a larger data type allows the compiler to automatically perform type casting without any issues. However, assigning a larger data type to a smaller one may lead to data loss, and therefore, the compiler raises an error or warning to prevent this. This is because the smaller data type may not have the capacity to store the larger value. In contrast, when a value of a smaller data type is assigned to a larger data type, the operation works fine because there is no risk of data loss.
Note: It is important to note that both size and range matter in automatic type conversion. For example, even though a long occupies 8 bytes and a float only 4 bytes, a long can be automatically type cast to a float because float has a larger range that can represent the value of long. Only similar numeric data types—such as byte, short, char, int, long, float, and double—can be type cast to each other using automatic or explicit conversion.

